1. Difference between Shallow Copy and Deep Copy in Collections

	Shallow Copy:
	Shallow copy creates a new collection object, but the elements inside the collection are not copied.
	Both the original and copied collections refer to the same objects in memory.
	If the internal objects are modified, the change will be visible in both collections.
	
	Deep Copy:
	Deep copy creates a new collection and also creates new copies of all the objects inside it.
	The original collection and copied collection are completely independent.
	Any modification in one collection does not affect the other.

2. How do you sort a collection?

	Collections in Java can be sorted using the Collections utility class.
	The method Collections.sort() is commonly used to sort elements of a list in ascending order.
	The elements must implement the Comparable interface. If we want custom sorting logic, we can use a Comparator interface.
	From Java 8 onwards, sorting can also be done using lambda expressions for simpler code.

3. How do you convert an array to a list?

	An array can be converted into a list using the Arrays.asList() method.
	This method takes the array as an argument and returns a list containing the elements of that array.
	The returned list is fixed in size, which means elements cannot be added or removed.

4. How do you convert a list to an array?

	A list can be converted into an array using the toArray() method.
	This method returns an array containing all the elements of the list.
	The type of the array can be specified so that the returned array matches the required data type.

5. What are Lambda Expressions?

	Lambda expressions were introduced in Java 8 to provide a shorter way to write anonymous functions.
	They are mainly used to implement functional interfaces, which contain only one abstract method.
	Lambda expressions help reduce the amount of code and make programs easier to read and maintain.
	They are widely used in collections, streams, and sorting operations.